\layout Section

Solving for MIM (and other) parameters
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Solving-for-MIM}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

A 
\emph on 
Measurement Equation
\emph default 
 (M.E.) is a mathematical description (model) of the combination of an observing
 istrument and the thing it observes.
 We will use two different instruments to measure the ionospheric TEC: an
 array of gound stations and satellites, and an array of LOFAR stations
 and astronomical radio sources.
 But although they are quite different, they both have an M.E.
 with the same generic form.
 If we 
\emph on 
measure
\emph default 
 a TEC sample 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{rs}$
\end_inset 

, as seen from the position 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y,z)$
\end_inset 

 receiver 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

, in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $(l,m)$
\end_inset 

 of source 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

, its 
\emph on 
predicted
\emph default 
 value 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{rs}$
\end_inset 

 is given by the M.E.: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{rs}(pp,qq)=M_{rs}(pp)+Q_{rs}(qq)\quad TECU\label{eq: ME_generic}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{rs}$
\end_inset 

 is the MIM-function (with MIM parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset 

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{rs}$
\end_inset 

 is an expression that contains measurement parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{m}$
\end_inset 

, i.e.
 the parameters of various error mechanisms.
 The latter have nothing to do with the ionosphere, but they do affect the
 TEC measurements.
 Examples of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{m}$
\end_inset 

 are satellite-station bias values, or selfcal phase-zeroes, or antenna
 phase errors introduced by the electronics or the troposphere.
 In sections 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Measuring-TEC-GPS}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Measuring-TEC-astro}

\end_inset 

 below, specific expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{rs}$
\end_inset 

 are given.
 
\layout Standard

The parameters of the M.E.
 (i.e.
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{m}$
\end_inset 

) may be estimated from the differences (residuals) 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{rs}$
\end_inset 

 between measured predicted values.
 Thus, each sample generates a (linear) equation of the form:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta_{rs}=P_{rs}(pp,qq)-S_{rs}=\sum_{k}\frac{\partial M_{rs}}{\partial p_{k}}\Delta p_{k}+\sum_{m}\frac{\partial Q_{rs}}{\partial q_{m}}\Delta q_{m}\label{eq: ME_normal}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Note that we can construct the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{rs}$
\end_inset 

 in different ways:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta_{rs}=(M_{rs}+Q_{rs})-S_{rs}=Q_{rs}-(S_{rs}-M_{rs})\label{eq: ME_resid}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

so instead of 'corrupting' the predicted value, we can also 'correct' the
 measured value with the inverse of (part of) the M.E.
 This is used in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Measuring-TEC-astro}

\end_inset 

, where the measured visibilities are corrected for the ionospheric phase,
 so they can be integrated without decorrelation.
\layout Standard

Fig 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:Simple-solver-diagram.}

\end_inset 

 shows a MeqTree diagram for solving for MIM (and other) parameters.
 Note that it has separate branches to produce the three kinds of equations:
 for GPS TEC measurements, for radio astronomical phase measurements, and
 for additional constraints to bridge the gaps in the MIM sampling function
 (see appendix 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec: Bridging-the-gaps}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

The 
\emph on 
variables
\emph default 
 these equations are the 
\emph on 
incremental
\emph default 
 improvements 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p_{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta q_{m}$
\end_inset 

 of the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}(t)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{m}(t)$
\end_inset 

