 to measure LOFAR beamshape parameters in the direction of fainter sources.
 
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

It is expected that GPS measurements will easily produce the differential
 accuracy that is needed for phase-locking.
 As a backup alternative, the following more cumbersome and time-consuming
 phase-locking procedure may be followed for LOFAR.
 A continuous selfcal phase solution on one or more bright sources starts
 with 3 stations in the core.
 The other stations are included one by one, moving outwards from the centre.
 The phase of this new station is varied by steps of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset 

, until the solution is consistent (phase-lock).
 Its phase will then be continuously tracked while the remaining stations
 are included, and during the subsequent observations.
\layout Standard

Note that phase-tracking takes the shape of an approximate MIM, i.e.
 a MIM in which the values of its parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}(t)$
\end_inset 

 are only accurate enough to give a phase accuracy better than a radian.
 Obviously, the measurement parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{k}$
\end_inset 

 must also be 'accurate enough' in this stage.
 The values of all parameter values are then improved in to the required
 level the subsequent stages.
 
\layout Subsection

Peeling
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Peeling}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\series bold 
NB: Simultaneous solutions are not possible, because we cannot pre-correct
 the visibilities for ionospheric phase.
 So, peeling is indispensible, once again.....
 
\layout Standard

Only the bright Cat I sources are used to estimate instrumental parameters
 (because, by definition, they are the only ones that give sufficient S/N
 in the available integration time).
 When there is more than one Cat I source in the field, one has the choice
 between two approaches.
 The first is making a single simultanous selfcal solution for all the relevant
 parameters.
 This is OK if there are only uv-plane effects, or if the number of direction-de
pendent parameters is small.
 Otherwise, the solution may become unstable because the number of parameters
 is too large.
 
\layout Standard

An alternative approach is 
\emph on 
peeling
\emph default 

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{JEN peeling}

\end_inset 

: A separate selfcal solution is made for each Cat I source, after which
 it is subtracted from the uv-data.
 Obviously, this must be done in order of decreasing apparent brightness.
 In this way, the number of parameters per solution never exceeds that of
 a 'classical' selfcal, i.e.
 with uv-plane effects only.
 Other advantages are smaller solution matrices (fewer parameters) and the
 possibility of shifting the phase centre of the uv-data to the position
 of the peeling source.
\layout Standard

A potential problem with peeling is the contamination caused by the other
 sources in the field.
 This will 'skew' the selfcal solution, and cause incomplete subtraction
 of the peeling source.
 The solution is to include a few of the brightest contamination sources
 in the selfcal predict.
 The prediction does not have to be very accurate, since contamination is
 non-linear.
 At the faint end, the 
\emph on 
collective
\emph default 
 contamination caused by the vector sum of many faint sources, that are
 distributed more or less homogeneoulsy, may be compensated by a gain factor
 (
\series bold 
called the Van der Tol factor, provided he comes up with an expression
\series default 
).
 Thus, at the cost of extra processing, the contamination can be reduced
 to an arbitrarily low level.
 
\layout Standard

Since each selfcal solution is independent, each solution will introduce
 a different selfcal offset.
 These have to be harmonized by the MIM.
 NB: A simultaneous solution for image-plane effects, i.e.
 independent phases in the direction of different sources, will also produce
 multiple independent offsets, just like peeling and rapid repointing.
 The reason is that, for each source direction, one may add an arbitrary
 phase offset to all the station phases.
 These will all cancel out in the differential phase of the measured visibility.
 
