Triple-frequency GPS
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Triple-frequency-GPS}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

For a particular receiver-satellite pair, we have three expressions for
 the phase-based observation of the receiver-satellite distance with the
 three frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset 

:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{i}=D+B_{i}+T\times C\times f_{i}^{-2}+\epsilon_{i}\label{eq: Li}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}$
\end_inset 

 is the observed distance (m) at frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset 

, D is the true distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset 

 is a bias term (
\begin_inset Formula $B_{rsf}=A_{rsf}+B_{rf}-B_{sf}$
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset 

 is the phase ambiguity, and the other 
\begin_inset Formula $B's$
\end_inset 

 are receiver and satellite biases), T is the TEC, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset 

 is an appropriate conversion constant, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset 

 is the measurement error.
 Forming the three possible differences, we get three new equations:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{ij}=L_{i}-L_{j}=(B_{i}-B_{j})+(\epsilon_{i}-\epsilon_{j})+T\times C\times(f_{i}^{-2}-f_{j}^{-2})\label{eq: Lij}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Without loss of generality, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}-B_{3}=(B_{1}-B_{2})+(B_{2}-B_{3})$
\end_inset 

.
 So then there are three equations, with three measurement values 
\begin_inset Formula $(L_{i}-L_{j})$
\end_inset 

, and three unknowns 
\begin_inset Formula $(B_{1}-B_{2})$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(B_{2}-B_{3})$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

.
 The measurement errors 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset 

 just contribute to the noise.
 
\series bold 
Therefore, we can directly determine the absolute TEC 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

.
 
\series default 
(Of course we also get the relative 
\begin_inset Formula $B's$
\end_inset 

, which may be used as an extra check on the solution, for instance by verifying
 that they are indeed 'constant' in time.)
\layout Standard

If we have only 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset 

 (i.e.
 if we only have two frequencies), then we have more unknowns than equations
 (either 3 unknowns from the 2 equations 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset 

 of the form 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq: Li}

\end_inset 

, or 2 unknowns from equation 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{12}$
\end_inset 

 of the form 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq: Lij}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

Unfortunately, the accuracy of the estimated TEC is very sensitive to the
 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{i}^{-2}-f_{j}^{-2})$
\end_inset 

 terms.
 The proposed 3rd frequency for Galileo is between the two regular frequencies,
 and (if I remember correctly), the absolute TEC measurement from Galileo
 (and probably GPS) would only be accurate to ~0.035 TECU, based on the current
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset 

 values.
